CatDescriptText: Leslie G. Moore, politicians, Schenley Heights, was part of the Pittsburghers Speak Up column, published in the Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, May 20, 1961, pg. 7 with question: "Do you think that Negroes today, in Pittsburgh, are prone to follow Negro leadership in politics or do they consider it ineffective?  What do you think about their attitude nationally?" answer reads: "The people must consider it to be ineffective because, well, just what has Negro leadership accomplished?  And as for the national level, well, my answer still stands..."
TitMainTitle: Two frames: Portrait of Leslie G. Moore wearing animal print blouse and hat, standing on Wood Street with Raab Clothes and Dimlings Candy in background, Downtown; Young boy and dog, seated on stoop outside of arched entryway of brick house with pediment and street number 4285, on hillside with lawn and stairway in foreground
